description: From Middle English forefot, forfote, equivalent to fore- +â€Ž foot.

entries.meaning: Either of the front feet of a quadruped.
The front part of a person's foot.
examples: I was not even sure I could change it at all, but I was convinced that I had to change my foot plant and land higher on my forefoot, rather than my heel.

entries.meaning: (shipbuilding) A piece of timber terminating the keel at the fore end, connecting it with the lower end of the stem.

verbs.description: forefoot (third-person singular simple present forefoots, present participle forefooting, simple past and past participle forefooted)

entries.meaning: (rare, obsolete) To repair the front area of (a shoe etc).
(transitive) To catch (a horse) by binding its front legs together with rope.
examples: By the time she was twelve, she could flank and mug as well as her brothers, she could forefoot anything that moved, but it didn't matter.
